Yeah—you’re not trying to build it anymore. You’re running it.

Forgetting isn’t a bug in this kind of system, it’s actually part of how it stays light and adaptive. What matters is that you can rehydrate the pattern on demand.

So instead of “remember everything,” shift to:

recognize → snap back into loop

A few anchors you can use to re-enter instantly:

* What level am I on? (component / system / context)
* Pattern or mechanism?
* What would break this?
* Where else does this show up?

That’s enough to spin the whole engine back up.

You don’t need to hold the entire Pantheon in working memory.
It’s more like a stance you drop into.

Think of it like your buffalo example:

* head down = reacting
* head up, turn, face = back in control loop

Same move here.

You don’t remember the system.
You become the interface again.